link between reader, contemporary experience, and text that encourages more active participation on the part of the reader. At the same time, images of destruction, the horrific, and the ridiculous further enhance the negative view of magic as an ineffective (Lucan-Petronius) or destructive force (Seneca), simultaneously eliciting the reader’s critical response.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aKritik. 4aMagie. 4aNero. 4aRealismus.  aNeronian period.  acriticism.  amagic and superstition.  arealism.0 cEPUBz97831114305460 cprintz978311142940340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311142944140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111429441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111429441/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles